Developing classification models to predict the success of bank telemarketing.

1. Introduction

The aim of this project is to develop classification models capable of accurately identifying customers willing to subscribe to long-term deposits based on their demographic and social characteristics. Additionally, we aim to assess the significance of these characteristics. By achieving these objectives, we could provide a valuable tool for banks to enhance their telemarketing efforts by focusing on customers more likely to meet the subscription criteria.

2. About the Dataset

The original data was collected from 2008 to 2010 from a Portuguese retail bank by Sergio Moro in his research paper “A data-driven approach to predict the success of bank telemarketing”. It contains 41188 observations with 21 variables related to bank client, product, and social-economic attributes. The dataset was obtained from UCI Machine Learning Repository for our analysis.

  • Original research paper: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S016792361400061X?via%3Dihub#preview-section-cited-by
  • Dataset retrieving source: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/222/bank+marketing

  • Hence, some of these highly correlated variables could be potentially removed to avoid multicollinearity issues when building the model.

4. Data pre-processing

4.1 Checking missing values

  • Checking missing values is important to ensure that the dataset is complete and free from missing or null values.
  • This is because missing values can lead to biased or incorrect results in the regression analysis later on.
any(is.na(bank.data))
## [1] FALSE

There is no missing value in the dataframe, hence there is no need to handle data in this regard.

4.2 Removing “duration”

  • We have discussed that ‘duration’ will not be useful in building a realistic predictive model as the duration seconds of the call cannot be known before the call is performed.
  • Hence, we will remove the column “duration”.
# Remove the 'duration' column
bank.data <- subset(bank.data, select = -duration)

4.3 Dealing with imbalanced data

As discussed in the EDA, the dataset was highly imbalanced in regards to the response variable.

# Get counts for 'deposit'
deposit_counts <- table(bank.data$deposit)

# Print counts
print(deposit_counts)
## 
##    no   yes 
## 36548  4640
# Calculate percentages
deposit_percentages <- prop.table(deposit_counts) * 100

# Print percentages
print(deposit_percentages)
## 
##       no      yes 
## 88.73458 11.26542

Only 4640 (11.27%) records show the successes of customers subscribing to deposit.

This is problematic since it could lead to severe reduction in accuracy of ML model we are attempting to build, as the highly unequal distribution in dependent variable of the training data makes the ML algorithm to become biased towards the majority class.

  • To tackle this unequal distribution, we could generate syenthetic data using ROSE (Random Over Sampling Examples) package in R.
  • ROSE uses k-nearest neighbors to create synthetic instances for the minority class, aiming to balance the class distribution.

We make the dataset suitable for ROSE

# To use ROSE, variables defined character should be converted to factor 
bank.data[] <- lapply(bank.data, function(x) if (is.character(x)) as.factor(x) else x)

4.4 Splitting traing & testing data and applying ROSE

We first divide the data in accordance with the recommended 8:2 ratio, which is considered optimal for training ML models

# Randomly splitting the data into training and testing datasets
set.seed(123)
train_index <- sample(nrow(bank.data), round(nrow(bank.data)*0.8))
bank.train <- bank.data[train_index, ]
bank.test <- bank.data[-train_index, ]
table(bank.train$deposit) 
## 
##    no   yes 
## 29185  3765
table(bank.test$deposit) 
## 
##   no  yes 
## 7363  875

We then apply ROSE to the training data

library(ROSE)
## Loaded ROSE 0.0-4
# Use the ROSE function to create a new training dataset with synthetic data
bank.train.rose <- ROSE(deposit ~ ., data = bank.train, seed = 123, N = nrow(bank.train)*2)$data
new_deposit_counts<- table(bank.train.rose$deposit)
new_deposit_counts
## 
##    no   yes 
## 33276 32624
# Calculate percentages
new_deposit_percentages <- prop.table(new_deposit_counts) * 100

# Print percentages
print(new_deposit_percentages)
## 
##       no      yes 
## 50.49469 49.50531

Hence, we have resolved the imbalanced class distribution, as 49.5% of records indicate the successes of customers subscribing to deposit.

5. Model Development

To achieve our research objectives, we can develop two different classification models: Logistic Regression model and Decision Tree model.

5.1 Logistic Regression Model

We will develop a logistic regression model, which is a supervised learning model that is commonly used to predict the probability of a binary event occurring.

Applying Stepwise Selection

Stepwise selection of minimizing the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) will be used to select the significant variables in the model.

  • Stepwise selection performs iterative process of selecting the optimal subset of variables for inclusion in a model.
  • AIC (Akaike Information Criterion): A measure of the relative quality of statistical models that is optimal when minimized
  • Backward Stepwise Selection will be conducted where we start with the full model (including all variables) and iteratively remove variables one at a time.

We first build a model including all variables.

# Initial logistic model 
model1<- glm(deposit~., data = bank.train.rose,family=binomial(link="logit"))

Apply Stepwise Selection.

library(MASS) # required library for Stepwise selection 
## 
## Attaching package: 'MASS'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     select
# applying the step function 
stepAIC(model1, direction = "backward", trace = FALSE)

Examining Multicollinearity

Now that we have checked the statistical significance of the predictors, we can examine multicollinearty among them.

  • Multicollinearity refers to the presence of high correlations between predictor variables in a regression model. It can cause issues in the estimation of coefficients and lead to unstable and unreliable results.
  • Multicollinearity can be examined via VIF (Variance Inflation Factor). VIF measures how much the variance of an estimated regression coefficient increases if the predictors are correlated.
  • VIF values greater than 5 are often considered indicative of multicollinearity.
library(car)
vif(stepmodel)

No concerns regarding multicollinearity was found.

Now that our model is finalized, let’s see how the model performs on the testing data.

# Make predictions on the testing data
predictions <- predict(stepmodel, newdata = bank.test, type = "response")

# Convert predicted probabilities to binary predictions (0 or 1)
predicted_classes <- ifelse(predictions > 0.5, 1, 0)

# Compare predicted classes with actual classes
conf_matrix <- table(predicted_classes, bank.test$deposit)

# Calculate accuracy rate
accuracy <- sum(diag(conf_matrix)) / sum(conf_matrix)
cat("Accuracy Rate:", accuracy, "\n")
## Accuracy Rate: 0.7608643

Hence, our final logistic regression model has the accuracy rate of 76.1%.

We will also develop a decision tree model , which is a supervised learning model used in classification task through the algorithm of building tree-like model by recursively splitting the training data based on the most informative features.

library(tree)

Pruning the decision tree model

Decision trees have a tendency to become overly complex and to overfit leading to poor performance on new, unseen data. Pruning is a technique to control the complexity of the tree by removing branches that do not contribute significantly to improving the model’s performance.

  • Pruning involves growing a large tree and then selectively removing branches. - Cross-validation helps assess the performance of the pruned tree on multiple subsets of the data, providing a more reliable estimate of its generalization ability.

We apply 10-fold cross-validation to find the optimal tree model.

# Applying cross-validation 
tree_cv = cv.tree(tree.m,FUN=prune.misclass)
tree_cv$size 
## [1] 7 6 5 3 2 1
tree_cv$dev 
## [1] 10225 10225 10907 12757 19649 32624
  • Tree models with 7,6,5,3,2,1 terminal nodes were found
  • They correspond to 10225, 10225, 10907, 12757, 19649, 32624 misclassification occasions
  • The minimum cv-misclassification value is 10225, corresponding to 7 or 6 terminal nodes

Since a tree model with less terminal nodes are generally easier to interpret, less prone to overfitting, and faster to compute, the pruned tree model with 6 terminal nodes can be considered as our final tree model.

# Generating fianl pruned tree model 
tree.final<- prune.misclass(tree.m, best=6)
plot(tree.final)
text(tree.final, pretty=0)

summary(tree.final)

We can then test the accuracy of our final tree model.

# Make predictions on the training data
tree_predictions <- predict(tree.final, newdata = bank.test, type = "class")

# Create a confusion matrix
tree_conf_matrix <- table(tree_predictions, bank.test$deposit)

# Calculate accuracy rate
tree_accuracy <- sum(diag(tree_conf_matrix)) / sum(tree_conf_matrix)
cat("Accuracy Rate:", tree_accuracy, "\n")
## Accuracy Rate: 0.881646

Our final tree model has the accuracy rate of 88.2%.

6. Model performance evaluation

This report aims to build a classification model for accurately identifying customers willing to make deposits, while also assessing the significance of demographic and socio-economic features in the model. The ultimate goal is to optimize the bank’s telemarketing strategy. - To achieve this objective, relying solely on classifier accuracy is deemed inadequate. - Therefore, various model performance evaluation criteria have been employed, taking into account business considerations.

6.1 Recall as the Evaluation Criterion

In the business perspective, there were two types of major errors that the model could make,

  • Predicting a customer would make deposit but they actually do not (False Positive) which could lead to loss of resources
  • Predicting a customer would not make deposit but they actually do (False Negative) which could lead to loss of potential profits.

As the bank’s main objective is to maximize profits, the ideal classifier model should be able to minimize the loss of potential profits. Hence, we can consider that Recall (TP/(TP+FN)), an indicator of False Negative rate, could be an appropriate metric to evaluate the performance of our models.

Calculating Recall rate on the final logistic regression model

# conf_matrix = confusion matrix for logistic model

# Extract values from the confusion matrix
true_positives <- conf_matrix[2, 2]
false_negatives <- conf_matrix[2, 1]

# Calculate recall
recall <- true_positives / (true_positives + false_negatives)
cat("Recall:", recall, "\n")
## Recall: 0.2608126

Calculating Recall rate on the final decision tree model

# tree_conf_matrix = confusion matrix for logistic model

# Extract values from the confusion matrix
tree_true_positives <- tree_conf_matrix[2, 2]
tree_false_negatives <- tree_conf_matrix[2, 1]

# Calculate recall
tree_recall <- tree_true_positives / (tree_true_positives + tree_false_negatives)
cat("Recall:", tree_recall, "\n")
## Recall: 0.4466951
  • The logistic regression model demonstrates the recall rate of 26.1%.
  • The decision tree model demonstrates the recall rate of 44.7%.

6.2 ROC AUC as the Evaluation Criterion

ROC (Receiving Operating Characteristics) curve is commonly used as a performance measurement of a classifier model at various threshold settings. AUC (Area Under the Curve) of the ROC curve indicates how much the model is capable of distinguishing between classes.

  • The ROC plots also show the trade-offs between specificity and sensitivity (Recall) at every possible threshold.
  • The higher the ROC AUC is, the better the model is at correctly classifying overall.

ROC AUC of the final logistic regression model

library(ROCR)

#calculating the predicted probability for 'Yes' using the test data
prob.log = predict(stepmodel, bank.test, type = "response")

# ROC curve for the final logistic regression model
pred.log = prediction(prob.log, bank.test$deposit)
log.roc = performance(pred.log,measure="tpr", x.measure="fpr")
plot(log.roc, lwd=2, colorkey=T, colorize=T, main="ROC curve on logstic model")
abline(0,1)

#evaluating the performance by calculating the area under the ROC curve 
performance(pred.log, measure="auc")@y.values 
## [[1]]
## [1] 0.7802394

ROC AUC of the final decision tree model

library(ROCR)

#calculating the predicted probability for 'Yes' using the test data
prob.tree = predict(tree.final, bank.test, type = "vector")[,2]

# ROC curve for the final tree regression model
pred.tree = prediction(prob.tree, bank.test$deposit)
tree.roc = performance(pred.tree,measure="tpr", x.measure="fpr")
plot(tree.roc, lwd=2, colorkey=T, colorize=T, main="ROC curve on tree model")
abline(0,1)

#evaluating the performance by calculating the area under the ROC curve 
performance(pred.tree, measure="auc")@y.values 
## [[1]]
## [1] 0.7634828
  • The logistic regression model demonstrates the ROC AUC score of 0.78.
  • The decision tree model demonstrates the ROC AUC score of 0.763.

7.2 Implications from the model

The variables used in the decision tree model were “pdays”, “euribor3m”, “previous”, and “month”.

  • “pdays”: Number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from the previous campaign
  • “euribor3m”: euribor 3 month rate — daily indicator
  • “previous”: Number of contacts performed before this campaign for this client
  • “month”: Last contact month

The implications suggest that the timing of the last contact, prevailing economic conditions, the history of contacts, and the month of contact are key factors influencing the outcomes of the campaign.

Understanding these factors can guide strategies for optimizing future marketing campaigns, such as targeting clients at specific times, considering economic conditions, and leveraging historical contact information.
